# Global Rules

- Always respond in 日本語
- I am a professional engineer. Prioritize quality and optimal implementation. No hand-holding, no unnecessary confirmations. Be concise when reporting.
- We have plenty of time and resources. No holding back, no conservative estimates. TODO comments are deferred problems — if information is missing, proactively gather it. Finish the job completely until the end without asking for allowance to stop halfway.

## Coding

- Follow best practices for each language/framework
- Bundler: Vite, Test: Vitest, Linter/Formatter: Biome
- Package manager: check for pnpm-lock.yaml / bun.lockb / uv.lock to determine which to use (pnpm, bun, uv)
- NEVER hardcode dependency versions in package.json / pyproject.toml. Always install via CLI commands to get the latest version.
- NEVER use linter-ignore directives (@eslint-ignore, @ts-ignore, @biome-ignore, etc.). If you need one, the code design is wrong — fix the root cause instead.

After implementation, run the linter and fix all issues until there are zero warnings/errors. Do not ignore any linter warnings/errors.
Then, write an implementation report to `kage1020/report-YYYY-MM-DD-NN.md` with the following format:
```
# Implementation Report
- Date: YYYY-MM-DD
- Summary: A brief summary of the implementation
- Details: A detailed explanation of the implementation, including design decisions, challenges faced, and how they were overcome.
- Next Steps: Any follow-up work or improvements that can be made in the future.
```

## TDD (t_wada style)

Implementation MUST follow this order:
1. Design — understand requirements and define the approach
2. Acceptance Criteria — write test cases as AC only (no test code yet). These are locked unless there's a compelling reason to change them.
3. Test implementation — write actual test code from the AC
4. Implementation — write production code to pass the tests
5. Iterate — fix tests / fix implementation until all tests pass

Never skip straight to implementation. Always start from design and AC.

## Git

- NEVER commit directly to main or dev branches. Always create a feature branch.
- Commit frequently to prevent code loss and maintain traceable history.
